<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>T 444E Diesel Engine Diagnostics (1997) - SECTION 3.5: CIRCUIT FUNCTION AND DIAGNOSTICS - EXHAUST BACK
        PRESSURE (EBP) SENSOR - FAULT DETECTION/MANAGEMENT
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="proctype" graphiccount="1">
        <title>FAULT DETECTION/MANAGEMENT</title>
        <para>An EBP signal that is detected out of range high or low by the ECM will cause the engine to ignore the EBP
            signal and disable exhaust back pressure operation.
        </para>
        <para>Refer to
            <emph type="bold">Figure
                <hotlnk xrefid="ef1251838">3.45</hotlnk>
            </emph>
            and
            <emph type="bold">Table
                <hotlnk xrefid="et1251806">3.11</hotlnk>
            </emph>
            for the circuit diagram and table of the Exhaust Back Pressure (EBP) Sensor.
        </para>
        <figure id="ef1251838" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="eg1121" filename="../figeg1/EG1121.webp" type="webp"/>
            <caption>Figure 3.45 - Exhaust Back Pressure Circuit</caption>
        </figure>
        <table id="et1251806">
            <title>Table 3.11 - Exhaust Back Pressure Sensor (EBP)</title>
